re, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1398–1476":"1398–1476","1417–Male":"1417–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1415":"1415","1476":"1476","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1370":"1370","AFT 1395":"after 1395","1417":"1417","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wyllys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Willis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Willis","meanings":["variant of   Will   with genitival <i>-s</i>. This surname represents a retention of the second syllable, introduced by the addition of the Middle English genitival suffix <i>-es</i>, which would have been pronounced in the Middle English period. Compare   Wills  . In some cases the name is a variant of   Willey  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","variant of   Willows  .","English:"]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Napton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Napton on the Hill (Warwicks), which is recorded as  <i>Nepton</i> in 1086,  <i>Neapton</i> in 1199, and  <i>Cnapton</i> in 1235. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>cnæpp</i> ‘hill-top, hillock, a short sharp ascent’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Nappin","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Napton  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Wyllys of Napton was born in 1395, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Richard Willes, was 25 and his mother, Mary Medows, was 21. He died in 1453, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1398–1476":"1398–1476","1417–Male":"1417–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1415":"1415","1476":"1476","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1370":"1370","AFT 1395":"pärast 1395","1417":"1417","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1398–1476":"1398–1476","1417–Male":"1417–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1415":"1415","1476":"1476","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1370":"1370","AFT 1395":"1395 jälkeen","1417":"1417","Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England":"Priors Marston, Warwickshire, England","Priors Marson, Warwickshire, , England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1395–1453":"1395–1453","1415–1482":"1415–1482","1398–1476":"1398–1476","1417–Male":"1417–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1375–1395":"1375–1395","1415":"1415","1476":"1476","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1370":"1370","AFT 1395":"après 1395","1417":"1417","Pri